post_text:
‘Twas the night before school started
When all through Patoka town
The parents were cheering
It was a riotous sound
By eight the kids were washed
And tucked into bed
When memories of homework
Filled them with dread
New pencils, clear backpacks, face masks too
New teachers, new COVID procedures - their anxiety grew
Parents just giggled when they learned of this fright
And shouted upstairs -
Go to bed it’s a school night!

See you tomorrow 💚💛

post_text:
Morning student drop off and student drivers demonstration video...enjoy! Bus riders will be dropped off at elementary doors.

- Drop off will be at the East door entrance.￼
- The Parent will pull up to the east entrance sidewalk and let the student proceed to the building. Staffel great the student and ask a series of health related yes or no questions. Questions consist of fever, cough, muscle aches, sore throat, runny nose, loss of taste or smell, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, shortness of breath, headache, close contact with someone with COVID-19 and temperature check. And a child with the temperature greater than 100.4 cannot enter the building.
- Once The student is masked and cleared to enter the building, a staff member will signal a parent and they may leave the school grounds.￼￼￼

post_text:
Here’s a demonstration video to help understand the new parent pickup procedure. This is NOT for kids who ride the bus. ENJOY 😉

- All students who are picked up by parents/guardians will be led to the gym at the end of the school day and kept at 6 feet social distancing.￼
- Parents are to remain in their vehicles and will form a single line in the south/staff parking lot. Staff, cones and/or some type of markers will be on the parking lot to signify the direction parents are to travel.￼
- Once the parent reaches the east door of the gym a staff member will greet them and radio into the gym for the child.
- As soon as the child is loaded and secure in the vehicle the parent is allowed to leave the school grounds.￼￼

Just a reminder....In house Parent Remote Learning/Google Training is scheduled for Tuesday, August 25th 2:00pm – 7:30pm and Wednesday, August 26th 9:00am – 2:30pm. We encourage all parents/guardians to register for this training. The training is for grades K-12. Elementary trainings are 30 minutes, junior high (6th-8th) and high school trainings are one hour. The training will help parents better understand how Google Classroom will be used in the child's classroom and in the event school is mandated to switch from in-person learning to remote. This is a teacher lead training and topics covered will be: remote learning procedures, logging into Google, a list of expectations, etc.

https://signup.com/go/bPnmbvL

post_text: Patoka CUSD #100 is taking applications for the following anticipated opening for the 2020-21 school year, full time high school Special Education Teacher. Individuals interested in this position must have an Illinois Professional Educator License endorsed in high school special education issued by the Illinois State Board of Education. Interested candidates please send a letter of interest, resume, copy of teaching license, copies of transcripts and 3 letters of recommendation to Mr. Justin Venhaus, 1220 Kinoka Road, Patoka IL 62875 by August 5, 2020. Patoka CUSD #100 is an Equal Opportunity Employer.

post_text: The Regional Office of Education #13 Preschool for All program at Patoka School invites children who will be 3 years old on or before September 1, 2020 to sign up for a Fall Preschool screening for possible enrollment! Please contact MacKenzie Webster at mwebster@roe13.org to receive an online screening questionnaire. An in person screening through KSED will take place at a later date. Preschool classes will attend school on an AB schedule with one day remote learning. Complete remote learning options are available for families that request them. Any child enrolled completely remote will still be enrolled in the PFA program and will be guaranteed a physical spot in the classroom if and when families choose to do so. We look forward to hearing from you!

post_text: Congrats to Patoka seniors, Jacob McCoy and Colton Hill!
shared_text:
Illini Team Trail
June 9 at 2:43 PM ·

TWO TEAMS,TWO SENIORS, AND TWO VICTORIES
Jacob McCoy and Colton Hill were both Seniors at Patoka High School 2019-2020. They missed out on everything that all seniors look forward to, including the High School Fishing Team. Jacob McCoy-Scott Bradley teamed up this year for their first year with ITT, as for their results, they took 1st Place in Illini Team Trails tournament on 5/31/2020 at Lake Shelbyville with 14.83 lbs. Wes Cummins-Colton Hill took 1st Place at Rend Lake the following week with 15.39 lbs. This is Colton's second year fishing with Wes. Congratulations to both of these young men as they start a lifelong passion of tournament fishing. Most of all, we want to thank Scott Bradley and Wes Cummins for taking on the privilege of teaching these two the skills and ethics to continue fishing competitively.These two seniors from Patoka Illinois will never forget this, thanks to both of you.

post_text:
Answers to some recent questions:

Grades: All teachers should be updating grades to Teacherease often to ensure students know if there is work they need to make up or if they want to redo an assignment.

Finals: Unfortunately, we have decided to cancel finals for our junior high and high school students. We understand their disappointment by this news, but we assure you we plan on returning finals, with all the happiness and excitement they bring, next school year.

Breakfast and Lunches: These will continue to be delivered until at least May 22nd. We await further instruction from the state if they are to continue after that.

We're happy to answer any other current or future questions anyone may have. We are doing our best to get as much information as we can out to the students, parents, and community members. We may forget some details and such along the way, so please do not hesitate to ask because you may not be the only one wondering.

Hope everyone is staying safe.

-Justin Venhaus

Finals: Unfortunately, we have decided to cancel finals for our junior high and high school students. We understand their disappointment by this news, but we assure you we plan on returning finals, with all the happiness and excitement they bring, next school year.

Breakfast and Lunches: These will continue to be delivered until at least May 22nd. We await further instruction from the state if they are to continue after that.

We're happy to answer any other current or future questions anyone may have. We are doing our best to get as much information as we can out to the students, parents, and community members. We may forget some details and such along the way, so please do not hesitate to ask because you may not be the only one wondering.

Hope everyone is staying safe.

-Justin Venhaus

post_text:
The Governor announced a stay-at-home order for all of Illinois that ends Tuesday, April 7, 2020.

For our Patoka School families, this means that our school closure is now extended through at least Tuesday, April 7, 2020 with the intent to open on Wednesday, April 8, 2020. At this time Easter Break will still be observed.

Patoka School will continue to make available free breakfast and lunch. You can call the school at 618-432-5440 if you would like to receive these meals.

Staff is currently working on subject grade level packets that will be available no later than next Tuesday. Staff is waiting on direction from the State as to what might be included in the subject and grade level packets.

We encourage everyone to follow the Governor's order and do your part to help others by practicing social distancing and proper hand washing.

If you have questions or need further information you can call the school at 618-432-5440.

Sincerely,

Mr. David H. Rademacher
Superintendent Patoka CUSD #100

Steve Gans is with Jeff Goodin and 10 others.
February 28 at 9:51 PM ·

‼️ POSTPONED‼️ due to shut down...

So here's what we've been working on.... The final piece of the 🧩
✅MARK your calendars for Sunday, March 29th at 6pm! We will be doing an all Patoka Alumni music concert in the Patoka High School gymnasium to raise money for the current band program! Admission at the door will be $10 for adults and $5 for students...
We're all EXCITED to be able to come back home where it all started for all of us, so we can give back and help the next generations pursue their hopes and dreams in the art of learning and playing music!! Alumni concert musicians that will be performing are....
Jamie Nattier(2008) John Spicer(2010) Drew Ray(2010) Katelyn Robinson(2010) Whitney Lowery(2010) Jacob Jenkins(2012) Kyle DeVore(1992) Nick Parker(1990) Dug Drenckpohl(1989) Steve Gans(1989) Jeff Goodin(1982) Tim Murfin(1983) Jeff Sturgeon(1983)
I'm with the band are you?!
-An online t-shirt link will be available soon!!
💚💛 Can't wait to see y'all💚💛

post_text: Students in 6th grade showed off their knowledge about genetics and heredity with Pedigree Power books. Each student created a family with a recessive superhero trait. They constructed 3 generations of the family and used Punnett squares to trace the superpower through the generations. They then wrote a story and created a book to go with their superhero families. Today, they shared their books with their classmates!

post_text:
Centralia, Illinois: The Marion County Coalition Against Drug Use will host a community event on January 28th from 6 until 8 PM at the Centralia Junior High Gymnasium. This event will be packed with information geared toward Parents, Guardians, and Educators regarding the recent legalization of cannabis in Illinois. Speakers will begin at 6 pm and will include local law enforcement, individuals in recovery, and an addiction counselor.
At the conclusion of the presentations there will be a panel discussion and time for audience questions. If you have questions that you can’t seem to find answers to this is an event you will not want to miss.
Please join the Marion County Coalition Against Drug Use on Tuesday, January 28th from 6-8 PM with speakers beginning at 6 for Marijuana: What Parents Need to Know about Legalization, at the Centralia Junior High Gym located at 900 S. Pine St., Centralia, IL.

A note from Nurse Ambria ~
I want to thank those of you who donated clothing/coats/shoes to the school. The donations are much appreciated! With those donations several bags have been given to children who can use them. I am happy to announce my office is overstocked with items. At this time, I can not accept anymore donations due to the over abundance of generosity. I will let you know when and what items can be accepted again.
Thank you for your support and understanding!
